Step 1. The Raw Dataset: Challenges Noticed
The initial dataset (all_inclusion_BI.xlsx) had:
•	Multiple measurement systems (Snellen, N-notation, S-cases).
•	Inconsistent formatting (e.g., 6/12+1, 6/7.5-1, 1MIN, Plano).
•	Duplicated or unclear columns (short vs long prescriptions, multiple time columns).
•	Blank or invalid entries.
•	Multi-layered features/ column headers 
This made direct analysis impossible especially in building a dashboard. The first task was to standardize everything to comparable values, especially vision acuity (VA).

Step 2. VA to logMAR Conversion Formula
Since the core of the analysis was vision outcomes, we focused on converting all VA measures to logMAR equivalents.
Basically, the formula followed the algorithm below:

IF the cell is blank OR equals "-":
    Return blank

ELSE
    Try:
        IF the cell contains "/":
            Extract numerator = text before "/"
            Extract denominator = text after "/"
            logMAR = log10(denominator / numerator)
            Round logMAR to 2 decimal places
            Return logMAR
        ELSE
            Return blank
    If any error occurs:
        Return blank
 
And the actual formula is: 

logMAR = log10(denominator / numerator)
 
Explanation of the formula: 
•	Checks if blank or invalid (-) then leaves empty.
•	If Snellen format (6/x), extracts the denominator and applies:
logMAR = log10(denominator/numerator).
•	Handles special cases (+1, –1, decimals) by adjusting with ±0.02 per line.
•	N-notation and S-cases were mapped using equivalent lookup logic.
This formula became the foundation of cleaning VA columns. Once standardized, logMAR values allowed meaningful comparisons between Screening, DOT, and Full Refraction.

Step 3: Column by column commentary
3.1. coding (patient ID)
•	Raw data: Alphanumeric IDs like NB001, KB002.
•	Issue: Mixed letters and numbers.
•	Fix: Split into prefix (letters) and number; Prefix later mapped to region and Number used as patient sequence/order.
Reason to keep: Provides patient-level traceability and allows regional slicers in the dashboard.
3.2 gender 
Raw data: “M”, “F”, blanks.
Fix: Retained blanks, replace – with blanks and ensured consistent upper case 
3.3	age & age_categories
Fix: Created categories: Teenagers (12–19), Young Adults (20–35), Middle-aged Adults (36–59), Older Adults (60+), Undeclared (blank entries)
Reason to keep: Tells the demographic story in a bar chart (Age distribution).
3.4	screening_va_ldu_both_logmar (Baseline VA)
Raw data: Snellen notations with inconsistencies (6/7.5-1, 6/12+1).
Fix: Applied VA to logMAR conversion formula.
Reason to keep: This is the baseline measure for unaided vision. Crucial for comparison against DOT and Full Refraction.
3.5	dot_va_dot_long_both_logmar (DOT Method – Distance)
Raw data: Same inconsistencies as screening.
Fix: Standardized via logMAR formula.
Reason to keep: Represents DOT performance for distance; compared with Full Refraction.
3.6	dot_va_dot_short_both_logmar (DOT Method – Near)
Raw data: Contained near VA (sometimes “N6”, “N8”).
Fix: Converted N-notation to approximate logMAR equivalents.
Reason to keep: Demonstrates DOT’s ability for near vision correction, complements distance results.
3.7	fullref_va_lda_both_logmar (Full Refraction – Distance)
Raw data: Gold standard refraction values.
Fix: Converted to logMAR.
Reason to keep: Benchmark for evaluating DOT method.
3.8	pres_lens_long_re / le & categories (Distance prescriptions)
Raw data: Values like +2.00, -1.50, Plano, blanks.
Fix: Categorized into: High / Moderate / Mild Myopia, Emmetropia (0), Hyperopia
Reason to keep: Tells the story of distance vision problems in the patient population. Displayed as a doughnut chart.
3.9	pres_lens_short_re / le & categories (Near prescriptions / Adds)
Raw data: Values like +1.25, +2.00, +3.00.
Fix: Categorized into: Low Add, Medium Add, High Add
Reason to keep: Shows near vision problems (presbyopia). Displayed as a separate doughnut chart.
3.10	 pupillary_distance & categories
Raw data: 0–4 mm values (too low compared to clinical norms, but consistent within dataset).
Fix: Categorized as Low / Normal / High.
Reason to keep: Adds detail on prescription fitting.
3.11	 rg_test_re_categories / rg_test_le_categories (RG Test)
Raw data: Mixed responses: “Both”, “Green”, “Red”, “Both – faded”.
Fix: Standardized into categories: Balanced, Overcorrected (Red bias), Undercorrected (Green bias)
Reason to keep: Visualized in a stacked bar chart → tells the story of prescription quality, not just outcome.
3.12	 time_taken columns (dot_time_taken_minutes & fullref_va_time_taken_minutes)
Raw data: Entries like 1MIN, 3, 3MIN.
Fix: Removed “MIN” suffix, converted to numeric minutes.
Reason to keep: KPI cards for efficiency comparison (Avg DOT vs Avg Full Refraction).
3.13	 Method (from Final Prescription file)
Raw data: In a separate sheet: “DOT Glasses”, “Full Refraction”, “Preferred”.
Fix: Merged into dataset via patient coding.
Standardized to DOT and FULL
Reason to keep: Used as slicer & category axis in RG Test Results chart → shows balance differences by method.

4. Why These Columns Made It to the Dashboard
Demographics (Gender, Age, Region) → who are the patients?
VA logMAR conversions (Screening, DOT, Full Refraction) → how much improvement is possible?
Prescriptions (Distance & Near categories) → what are the main vision problems?
RG Test Results → how balanced are the corrections?
Efficiency (Time taken) → how practical is DOT compared to Full Refraction?
















